{{other uses|Midnight ramble (disambiguation)}}
A '''midnight ramble''' was a [[racial segregation|segregation]]-era midnight showing of films for an [[African American]] audience, often in a cinema where, under [[Jim Crow laws]] they would never have been admitted at other times.<ref>{{cite AV media|last1=Bowser|first1= Pearl |last2=Cram|first2=Bestor (dirs.)|year= 1994|title= Midnight Ramble: The Story of the Black Film Industry|series= The American Experience|publisher=PBS|format= DVD. 2009|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=Cincinnati World Cinema|year= 2007|url=http://www.cincyworldcinema.org/z_71020mr.php |title=Film Notes for "Midnight Rambles|ref=harv}}</ref> The films shown were often from among the over 500 films that were made between 1910 and 1950 in the United States with black producers, writers, actors and directors.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thomas|first= Pamela|year= 2011|url=http://blackfolksmakemovies.tripod.com |title=Black Folks Make Movies|ref=harv}}</ref>

